{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a884c042-6459-4606-9eb0-f6702a1a1c24","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 behavioral changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy** from `DisplayName` to `FullyQualifiedName`. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so every test looks new.\n\n**Fix** â€” add to a `.runsettings` file:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** â€” it's not associated with any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` (line 13 in your code) throws because no test is running yet.\n\n**Fix** â€” remove that access from `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is NOT available here in v4.\n    // Use the instance TestContext property inside [TestInitialize] or [TestMethod] instead.\n}\n```\n\n## Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled by default at the **method** level. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable if tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **Timeout default** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CooperativeCancellation` by default (via `CancellationToken`), not `Thread.Abort`. |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on doubles** | Floating-point comparisons are stricter; use the overload with a `delta` parameter. |\n| **`[DataRow]` enum coercion** | Implicit intâ†’enum conversion in `[DataRow]` attributes no longer happens; pass the typed enum value. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | The collection is now read-only in some lifecycle phases. |\n\nThe parallel-execution change is the most likely to cause subtle new failures if your tests share static state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eab94b21-eca7-4e74-9696-a7a00a28e9bc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can address the user's questions with the context of their code. Let me provide a comprehensive answer about the MSTest v4 breaking changes they're encountering.\n\n1. **Test IDs changed** â€” MSTest v4 switched to fully qualified test IDs by default. This causes Azure DevOps (and other CI systems) to see every test as a \"new\" test, losing history. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` to `DisplayName` in the runsettings or project file.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** â€” In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a class-level context, not associated with any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` throws because there's no test running yet at class-initialization time. This is a behavioral change from v3 where it somewhat arbitrarily had the name of the first test.\n\n\n3. **Other notable changes** â€” There are several other areas worth being aware of: `[DataRow]` attributes may behave differently, parallel execution settings have shifted, `DeploymentItem` handling has changed, `TestContext.Properties` access patterns differ, and some Assert methods have been updated or removed.","outputTokens":826,"requestId":"0421:11F50C:1DFBF16:22158C4:69E836AF"},"id":"0f8eecef-c30f-4f74-afcd-226d1762c281","timestamp":"2026-04-22T02:47:29.092Z","parentId":"bf4a415d-fd06-4414-af51-d44ba49974cc"}
